Itay Michaeli -- Citi -- Analyst

Maybe just first a couple of financial questions. Paul, any thought to where U.S. dealer inventory could end the year? And with the new tools that you've implemented for ordering, any updated thoughts on how you're thinking about running dealer inventory, let's say over the next couple of years?

Paul Jacobson -- Chief Financial Officer

Yeah. Good morning, Itay. Thanks for the question. You know, I think -- I don't think anybody would say that dealer inventory levels are optimized right now, just drive by some lots and you see empty lots.

You certainly mean that we're operating much, much lower than what I think -- we even think is optimal. But you know, as we mentioned in the comments, there's a lot of tools that we're learning how to operate at these lean levels that I think will provide some long-term efficiencies. And the dealer network has done really an amazing job of not only working with us but also providing an environment for the customer that where the vehicle may not be immediately available. They give them reassurance to help drive that purchase transaction versus the customer being disappointed that the vehicle that he or she wants, doesn't want isn't there on the lot.

So that visibility, I think, undoubtedly will help us over the long term. And you know, we're taking those lessons and we're figuring out how to make sure that we manage that as efficiently as we can. But you know, we certainly came into the year expecting to build inventories out of -- coming out of the COVID situation. That clearly is a challenge amid some of the production issues that we've seen with the semiconductor shortage.

But you know, we certainly hope to build as we get into perhaps late 2021 into 2022 to start getting inventory levels that what we think is a much safer value to have vehicles on the lots where customers want to purchase them.

Itay Michaeli -- Citi -- Analyst

That's helpful. I appreciate all the detail, Paul. Maybe just one strategic question. Actually, on AV, of the 27 billion of us spend on EV and AV, can you maybe dimension how much of it is going toward the AV side and how much of that maybe is outside of Cruise? I'm kind of trying to get a sort of -- maybe if you can give us a bit of a sense of your vision for autonomy on the GM consumer vehicles, you know, whether Cruise may or may not play a role within that and kind of how you see that developing over the next several years as part of that to the other company?

Mary Barra -- Chairman and Chief Executive Officer

Sure. Well, you know, our focus at Cruise is to get create the technology that's safer than a human driver and deploy it in our first market from a commercialization perspective, and then we'll continue to expand that into other cities. And you know, we're really excited with the progress they're showing in San Francisco. Obviously, Dubai is very significant as well.

So you take that and, you know, I've always said we have kind of a revolutionary and an evolutionary strategy around driver assistance all the way to full Level 4, Level 5 autonomy. You see Cruise really focused on that, you know, full autonomy. But Super Cruise, we continue to add more and more features and we've said that you know, we've envisioned that to get 95% of being able to handle all solutions. You know, later in the decade, I believe, there's a lot to still unfold but I believe we'll have personal autonomous vehicles and then that will leverage the capability we have at Cruise with the capability that we have a car company to really be well-positioned to delight the customers from that perspective.

So both paths are very important because the technology we put on vehicles today, I think, makes them safer and delights the customers and is going to give us an opportunity for subscription revenue. And then the ultimate work that we're doing at Cruise, I think -- that is full autonomous, really opens up more possibilities and I think we can outline today.

Itay Michaeli -- Citi -- Analyst

That's all very helpful. Thanks so much. 

Mary Barra -- Chairman and Chief Executive Officer

Thank you, Itay.

Operator

The next question comes from the line of Emmanuel Rosner with Deutsche Bank.

