John Murphy -- Bank of America Merrill Lynch -- Analyst

Good morning, everybody. Hi, Mary. So you know, I just want to get back into this question of the inventory being too tight or light. And you know, I mean, you just put up a record quarter and you're telling us that the inventory is not optimal and it's too light.

I mean, would you argue that record profits indicate that you're in an optimal inventory? I mean, you know, it's --  the industry has gone through this, and we've been covering this for, you know, a few decades now where the inventory has been out of whack and too high, and now suddenly it's supposedly too tight. We're seeing record profits put off. I mean, is it really too tight? And what do you mean by going back to something this more normal? I mean, I look at the last three quarters, I mean, I think, the intro is 492,000 in the third quarter of last year and now you're 335. So is it somewhere in that zip code? Because I mean, you just put up the best record of a stretch I think GM has had in history with this inventory that's not optimal or too tight.

It just seems like you shouldn't change that much. What do you mean by growing the inventory?

Mary Barra -- Chairman and Chief Executive Officer

So, John, I think you're right that we'll never go back to that levels of inventories that we held post or pre-pandemic because we've learned we can be much more efficient getting the right models to the right dealers and leveraging and not having as much on the lot. But there are still customers who want to walk into a dealership and walk out or drive off the dealership with a brand-new vehicle. And we've got to be responsive to those customers as well. So you know, I think it's going to end up being a little higher especially when you look at our dealer network.

You know, I've got them sending me pictures that they have virtually nothing on the lot. So there's an optimal level significantly lower than it was in the past but higher than it is now. I think what you're seeing now though is the ingenuity of our dealers and the new tools we've provided that give them insight into what's coming and they're selling deep not only into the inventory but deep into the pipeline of vehicles that are on the way. So you know, I credit, you know, just how dedicated this team is of satisfying every customer.

But I think there's an optimal level that's a little higher than we have right now.

John Murphy -- Bank of America Merrill Lynch -- Analyst

I just think you're being sort of too apologetic. And the ingenuity you're forcing on the whole chain is actually driving a better outcome you've ever had before. It just seems like you're doing, you know, in some ways you'll be forced that -- the value chain is being forced in doing the right thing and you're -- that ingenuity should continue. It's not like you're if you're keeping that up but I mean, I just think rebuilding inventory too much might be not exactly the right answer. 

Mary Barra -- Chairman and Chief Executive Officer

So, John, to be clear, we won't overbuild inventory, to be crystal clear. And we will keep the ingenuity, the tools, I mean, because it's better for everybody. 

John Murphy -- Bank of America Merrill Lynch -- Analyst

Absolutely.

Mary Barra -- Chairman and Chief Executive Officer

It's better for their car company, it's better for the dealer.

John Murphy -- Bank of America Merrill Lynch -- Analyst

