Joseph Spak -- RBC Capital Markets -- Analyst

Paul, I fully appreciate, and you said this -- you know, the timing is difficult given everything going on in the industry. But you did say, you know, the first quarter came in better. So, I guess the implication is that very little of that semi-impact that you called out for the year happened in the first quarter. And then you've always called the second quarter worse, but it does seem like maybe it's a little bit worse than a few months ago.

So, at least that's the impression I got. And since you didn't give more clear color on implied second quarter, I think what would really help investors here is if you could compare that second-quarter production maybe versus expectations at the beginning the year. And then as we go forward for the rest of the year, you know, you mentioned GMF is better, we saw that in the guidance. But what -- and you mentioned pricing, but what are you, I guess, specifically assuming or how are you thinking about modeling pricing to offset things like higher commodities?

Paul Jacobson -- Chief Financial Officer

So, thanks for that question, Joe. You know, I think I'd go back to the fact that, you know, this is obviously a very dynamic situation. You know, I would say in all honesty that Q2 is probably worse than we expected. It was going to be a few months ago, but that's due in part to, you know, some of the timing of how we map this out.

So, you know, what I would say is that we are carefully evaluating the short-term supply chain, the intermediate-term supply chain, and some of the longer-term issues as well. So, you know, depending on the confidence of where we see chips coming in and which chips, and our ability to reallocate those and reprioritize those, you know, we did see an opportunity to accelerate some production into Q1 to take advantage of the market that we see right now, which is obviously very, very strong and the confidence to be able to make up some of that volume in Q2. So, that's why I think, you know, we need to be really cautious as we're thinking about the full year. You know, what gives us confidence is the agility that the team has displayed and being able to respond to this, and how dynamic it really is.

So, you know, part of the reason we don't want to anchor in on production volumes and so on is just because, you know, that's going to change. It's going to change next week. It's going to change the week after. Sometimes, it's better.

Sometimes, it's worse. So, you know, it's really trying to operate in at this level of, you know, where we need to take go-to-market strategies, where we need to prioritize mix, where we need to accelerate or potentially shut down a plant in anticipation of some challenges that are coming up over the short to medium term then. That's kind of what we're doing. You saw that going into plant downtime in Q1.

So, I wouldn't say that Q1 was immune from the semiconductor challenges. I think, certainly, the consumer has proven to be very robust, used car values continue to go up, which I think is endemic of the inventory challenges that we see across the board and that everybody sees. So, all of that is just -- is working in concert into, you know, what I would say is a very agile plan for us to meet our objectives. It's also why, you know, we're trying to steer this to the first half versus Q1 and Q2.

So, there isn't a -- there isn't necessarily a read-through in the short term because, you know, something that happens in March versus something that happens in April isn't really all that relevant to how we're thinking about managing through this. And that's why, you know, we have the confidence of looking at where first-half expectations were despite the disparity between Q1 and Q2. We actually think that we're performing ahead of expectations that were outweighed at the beginning of the year. We just want to be cautious about that in the back half.

Does that make sense?

Joseph Spak -- RBC Capital Markets -- Analyst

Yeah, no doubt. But so, is it fair to assume that embedded within that the second-half versus first-half pricing does take a step down?

Paul Jacobson -- Chief Financial Officer

No, I don't necessarily think that's the case. You know, I think the environment is what it is and, you know, that's kind of what puts us in that $5.5 billion-ish-type EBIT adjusted for the first half of the year. But, you know, the environment has remained strong. In some cases, it's gotten even stronger through the year.

So, you know, we're meant to capitalize on that wherever we can. But I don't see in our second quarter any sort of immediate changes to the pricing environment that we've seen today.

Joseph Spak -- RBC Capital Markets -- Analyst

